## Crash Description

https://console.firebase.google.com/u/0/project/expensify-mobile-app/crashlytics/app/android:org.me.mobiexpensifyg/issues/af3985b17bad9e9e418b98b7168b33f1?time=7d&types=crash&versions=9.3.19-4%20(509031904);9.3.19-3%20(509031903);9.3.19-0%20(509031900)&sessionEventKey=699301EE027500015D088E24447AF092_2185872096679185833

On HybridApp Android, a fatal `RuntimeException` occurs in `SlidingMenuController.js` when the user navigates to the Trips page. The crash is caused by calling `.getID()` on a `null` return value from `getActivePolicy()`.

**Crash location:** `Mobile-Expensify/app/Controllers/SlidingMenuController.js` line 397:

```javascript
policyID: self.app.getActivePolicy().getID()
```

## Root Cause Analysis

This is inside the `TRIPS` page handler, which first checks `self.app.isTravelEnabled()` (line 395). If that returns `true`, it proceeds to call `self.app.getActivePolicy().getID()` — but `getActivePolicy()` can return `null`.

**Why it returns null:** In `Mobile-Expensify/app/expensify.js` (line 6077), `getActivePolicy()` returns `null` when no valid policy is found, and also triggers a sign-out:

```javascript
if (!_.isPolicy(policy)) {
    yaplShowGrowl('Something went wrong, please sign in and try again');
    this.signOut();
    return null;
}
```

**The race condition:** `isTravelEnabled()` calls `getActivePolicy()` internally (line 7707) and succeeds. But by the time the code calls `getActivePolicy()` again on line 397, the policy may have been invalidated (e.g., sign-out started, or policy data cleared), causing `null` to be returned and `.getID()` to crash with a `TypeError: Cannot read properties of null`.

## Proposed Fix

Add a null guard before calling `.getID()`, or cache the `activePolicy` result from the `isTravelEnabled()` check:

```javascript
if (pageName === SlidingMenuController.PAGES.TRIPS) {
    var activePolicy = self.app.getActivePolicy();
    if (activePolicy && self.app.isTravelEnabled()) {
        API.Travel_GenerateSpotnanaToken({
            policyID: activePolicy.getID()
        })
        // ... rest of handler
    }
}
```

This avoids the double call to `getActivePolicy()` and eliminates the window for the race condition.

